> This Beef Mince and Potato Keema is bursting full of flavours and makes the perfect
> dinner night option. Cook up a fresh start!

If you don't have a toaster, heat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7 for
the naans.

Heat a large #saucepan{} on medium-high heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the @British Beef Mince{240%grams} and fry until browned,
~{4-5%minutes}. Use a #spoon{} to break it up as it cooks.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

Meanwhile, chop the @Baking Potato{1} into small 2cm chunks (no need to peel).

> TIP: They'll cook quicker if small.

Cut the @Plain Naans{2} in half widthways, then set aside.

Open the @Korma Curry Paste{50%grams}, @Curry Powder Mix{1%sachet}, and
@Tomato Puree{30%grams} sachets.

When the mince has browned, drain and discard any excess fat.

Stir in the korma curry paste, curry powder, tomato puree, @Chicken Stock Paste{10%grams},
potatoes, @Water{300%ml} for the sauce and half the @Mango Chutney{40%grams}.

Bring to the boil, then reduce the heat.

Pop a #lid{} on the pan and simmer until the sauce has thickened and the mince
and potato are cooked, ~{15-20%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Just before the keema is ready, warm the naan halves in your #toaster{} until
golden.

If you're using the oven, put the naans onto a #baking tray{}. Sprinkle with a
little water and pop them into the oven to warm through, ~{2-3%minutes}.

When the keema is ready, season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and remove from the
heat. Add a splash of water if needed.

Spoon your keema into #bowls{} and drizzle over the remaining mango chutney.

Serve the naan on the side. Enjoy!